    <h1 class="opener__hed  -is-over-bg opener__hed--light opener__hed--small" >        They Were Wrongfully Convicted. Now They’re Denied Compensation Despite Michigan Law.
    </h1>

    <div class="article-meta-1  -is-over-bg article-meta-1--light">
        <span class="article-meta-1__byline">
            by <a class="name" href="https://www.propublica.org/people/anna-clark">Anna Clark</a>, photography by <a class="name" href="https://www.propublica.org/people/sarahbeth-maney">Sarahbeth Maney</a>        </span>
        <time class="article-meta-1__pubdate">
            <time class="timestamp" datetime="2024-01-02EST05:00">Jan. 2, 5 a.m. EST</time>
        </time>
    </div>

    </div> <!-- Close .opener__topic-title-dek-wrapper -->

    <div class="content"> <!-- not sure if this is the best way to reestablish the text column -->
        <h2 class="opener__dek opener__dek--match-text-column" >            The state can provide the wrongfully convicted compensation of $50,000 for each year of incarceration, but the law’s narrow criteria and confusion over eligibility leave former prisoners facing another system that seems stacked against them.
        </h2>
    </div>

</div>
        
<div class="article-meta-1
     article-meta-1--left      article-meta-1--hide-byline " data-pp-location="article meta">

    <span class="article-meta-1__byline" data-pp-location="article byine">
        by <a class="name" href="https://www.propublica.org/people/anna-clark">Anna Clark</a>, photography by <a class="name" href="https://www.propublica.org/people/sarahbeth-maney">Sarahbeth Maney</a>    </span>
    <time class="article-meta-1__pubdate">
        <time class="timestamp" datetime="2024-01-02EST05:00">Jan. 2, 5 a.m. EST</time>
    </time>

