                            data-sizes="auto"
                            data-srcset="https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20180727-Cooper-3x2.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fp-x=0.5209&amp;fp-y=0.1882&amp;h=75&amp;q=70&amp;w=75&amp;s=4dd72b642a7abec735625f97180a93d7 75w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20180727-Cooper-3x2.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fp-x=0.5209&amp;fp-y=0.1882&amp;h=150&amp;q=70&amp;w=150&amp;s=a243f0f4fde8928382db3949aa446f76 150w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20180727-Cooper-3x2.jpg?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fp-x=0.5209&amp;fp-y=0.1882&amp;h=400&amp;q=70&amp;w=400&amp;s=dfe5e553d9c3fda5db0fa9dcf6ebb6f2 400w"
                            />
                    </div>
                
            
            <div class="story-promo__info" dir="auto">
                <strong class="story-promo__hed">Wrongly Convicted Man Receives $7.5 Million Settlement in Indiana</strong>
                            </div>
        </a>

    
</aside>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="64.0">A recent analysis by Gutman found that 71 compensation claims in Michigan have been granted, 24 have been denied and eight are pending. Three people who were wrongfully imprisoned haven’t yet filed claims but are within the three-year window to do so. According to a recent report from the attorney general’s office, the state has paid out about $50 million through WICA as of late 2023.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="65.0">For Gilbert Poole, money from the compensation fund was life-changing. In 2021, at age 56, he was freed from prison after serving nearly 32 years of a life sentence for murder. His conviction was overturned after his case was investigated by the Cooley Innocence Project and the attorney general’s conviction integrity unit.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="66.0">Poole’s claim was approved within weeks of his filing, and he said he received the money — nearly $1.6 million — within six months. “Without anybody opposing me, it went through pretty quick,” he said.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="67.0">That mattered because Poole was starting from scratch. He’d spent most of his life behind bars. He’d never used a cellphone. His parents had died. The only people he knew outside prison were lawyers and clergy who supported his case. But, Poole said, “you can’t really call them at 3 a.m. and say, ‘Hey, I can’t sleep,’ or ‘I’m having a panic attack,’ you know?”</p>
        
    
                    

<figure
    data-pp-id="68"
    data-pp-blocktype="image"
    class="bb-image size12 center  wide-sm wrap 
                ">

    


                    
    


    <img
        class=""
        alt=""
        width="7000"
        height="4669"
        loading="lazy" js-autosizes        src="https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20231130-Maney-WrongfulImprisonmentFund-081.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=534&amp;q=75&amp;w=800&amp;s=f6e2203c802a42f9b7165c776d72c886"
        srcset="https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20231130-Maney-WrongfulImprisonmentFund-081.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=267&amp;q=75&amp;w=400&amp;s=e61ed79562b8b6335f89354f24baaa6f 400w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20231130-Maney-WrongfulImprisonmentFund-081.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=534&amp;q=75&amp;w=800&amp;s=f6e2203c802a42f9b7165c776d72c886 800w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20231130-Maney-WrongfulImprisonmentFund-081.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=800&amp;q=75&amp;w=1200&amp;s=83c8865a5b1b9aec78ed4e692ce50c06 1200w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20231130-Maney-WrongfulImprisonmentFund-081.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=867&amp;q=75&amp;w=1300&amp;s=3c6d99c0f9e63988d4921f8dcbf26827 1300w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20231130-Maney-WrongfulImprisonmentFund-081.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=967&amp;q=75&amp;w=1450&amp;s=e8239374a85ea72088959988b41b2d0a 1450w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20231130-Maney-WrongfulImprisonmentFund-081.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1067&amp;q=75&amp;w=1600&amp;s=94fce3fdee6813fe6ed87df5b8011479 1600w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20231130-Maney-WrongfulImprisonmentFund-081.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1334&amp;q=75&amp;w=2000&amp;s=492a1dd55aa171fbbba08b806dbf71bd 2000w"
                    />

            
    
<figcaption class="attribution">
        <span class="attribution__caption">Gilbert Poole in his home in Holt, Michigan. “I was in there longer than I was out here. A couple years of adulthood and then the rest in prison,” said Poole, who spent nearly 32 years wrongfully imprisoned. “When I came out, I had to learn everything.”</span>
    
    
    
    </figcaption>

</figure>

        
    
                    

<figure
    data-pp-id="69"
    data-pp-blocktype="image"
    class="bb-image size09 center  wide-sm wrap 
                ">

    


                    
    


    <img
        class=""
        alt=""
        width="7000"
        height="4669"
        loading="lazy" js-autosizes        src="https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20231130-Maney-WrongfulImprisonmentFund-099.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=534&amp;q=75&amp;w=800&amp;s=4949d119671619b9353043a9658c3373"
        srcset="https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20231130-Maney-WrongfulImprisonmentFund-099.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=267&amp;q=75&amp;w=400&amp;s=7e04656abd2442fcb03106d913da3b91 400w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20231130-Maney-WrongfulImprisonmentFund-099.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=534&amp;q=75&amp;w=800&amp;s=4949d119671619b9353043a9658c3373 800w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20231130-Maney-WrongfulImprisonmentFund-099.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=800&amp;q=75&amp;w=1200&amp;s=4cea02ab2110cd62a28af39c06bf1df5 1200w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20231130-Maney-WrongfulImprisonmentFund-099.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=867&amp;q=75&amp;w=1300&amp;s=2d9b2ebf08c2d997d42a19458ef9a94b 1300w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20231130-Maney-WrongfulImprisonmentFund-099.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=967&amp;q=75&amp;w=1450&amp;s=234965b8608c0ba401ab494713ac07a6 1450w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20231130-Maney-WrongfulImprisonmentFund-099.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1067&amp;q=75&amp;w=1600&amp;s=50637b3e73c0ca17c7f26db65254b399 1600w, https://img.assets-d.propublica.org/v5/images/20231130-Maney-WrongfulImprisonmentFund-099.JPG?crop=focalpoint&amp;fit=crop&amp;fm=webp&amp;fp-x=0.5&amp;fp-y=0.5&amp;h=1334&amp;q=75&amp;w=2000&amp;s=681e5bb19d00f4d030e33d6d4683cb08 2000w"
                    />

            
    
<figcaption class="attribution">
        <span class="attribution__caption">Poole shares a self-portrait from his time in prison. He often used painting to imagine himself outside prison walls. “The best I can do is paint myself in there,” he said. “I couldn’t go there because I was in prison.”</span>
    
    
    
    </figcaption>

</figure>

        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="70.0">Poole bought a house outside Lansing that he’s renovating himself. He built a pole barn for tinkering, maybe even a place to start his own business. He bought a GMC Acadia. He meets with a therapist. And he’s saving and investing as best he can, he said, in hopes of making up for decades of lost wages, retirement savings and Social Security.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="71.0">Poole’s case moved unusually quickly. The time between the filing of a claim and the conclusion of their case ranges between one month and 52 months, according to <a href="https://www.law.umich.edu/special/exoneration/Documents/UTM%20Michigan.pdf">a 2023 study by Gutman</a>. The average is 16.7 months.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="72.0">For people trying to rebuild their lives, every day counts.</p>
        
    
                    
<p data-pp-blocktype="copy" data-pp-id="73.0">“It’s just heartbreaking to know that it can be so difficult to get even the most basic necessities when you come home from a wrongful conviction,” said Kenneth Nixon, who spent nearly 16 years in prison for murder before his conviction <a href="https://www.medill.northwestern.edu/news/2021/kenneth-nixons-conviction-overturned-two-years-after-medill-students-investigation.html">was overturned in 2021</a>. Less than a year after he filed his WICA claim, the court of claims ordered the state to pay him about $515,000 in compensation, less than he had sought.</p>
        
    
                    

<figure
    data-pp-id="74"
    data-pp-blocktype="image"
    class="bb-image size13 center  wide-sm wrap 
                ">

    


                    
    


